column3: “How can we improve our SaaS homepage?” I get this question 100s of times. SaaS founders know that the homepage is the most important page of their SaaS website. Still the struggle with: → Telling their story.→ Keeping users engaged. → Getting users to actually signup. Let’s face it. SaaS founders are great at building their product. Theyre not always so great in turning all that knowledge and passion into something everyone understands. They have an OK website. But they still end up with: → Low signup rates.→ High bounce rates.→ Leaving $$$ on the table. Time to fix that. I’ve created a simple blueprint that you can apply today. Follow the structure and I guarantee you will see an increase in your signup rate. You’re homepage isn’t just your first page. It’s your first impression.
column7:
It took me multiple homepage redesigns to learn what actually moves signups.

  A founder I worked with focused the hero on one outcome. We reshaped the structure into a simple blueprint and saw a 25% increase in signups within weeks.

  Structure beats storytelling that tries to say everything.

  Which single outcome would you pick for your homepage?
column8:
Most founders treat the homepage like a product tour, not a conversion funnel.

  That approach buries the signup path and confuses visitors. I recommend a tight blueprint and clear next steps instead of long feature lists.

  Make the path to signup obvious and short.

  Which step feels unnecessary on your current homepage?
column9:
When was the last time you treated your homepage as a hypothesis?

  I tell clients to run small experiments on structure and track the signup flow. The wins are often surprising and cheap to test. Reframing the homepage as testable cuts wasted effort.

  Design for change, not perfection.

  What hypothesis would you test first?

column3: From a website built in PHP, only manageable by a developer, to a site that can be updated in minutes by any team member. Cibus is leading an agricultural revolution. And now they’ve started their own digital revolution. New page, edit content, swap a video? Done in minutes. All thanks to this component-based Webflow site. Anyone on the team can drag and drop new elements onto the page. Everything stays responsive. Everything stays on-brand. That’s the power of combining system thinking with sharp branding. The visual identity by @momkai frames the corps as the heroes of this revolution. While the website components are the hero of the digital revolution. Branding + Web design by Momkai Development by Patrick Huijs
column7:
It took a rebuild to see how much autonomy matters for a team.

  A client moved from dev-only updates to component-driven pages in Webflow. Suddenly marketing could launch campaigns without waiting weeks.

  Component systems make teams faster and reduce friction.
  How do you keep components consistent across new pages?
column8:
Pattern I see often: strong branding, weak operational thinking.

  Visual identity can shine while the site still requires developer edits. Combining system thinking with brand guidelines fixes that gap.

  Design systems should serve both brand and operations.
  Who owns the component library in your team?
column9:
When brand work meets system thinking, teams actually ship more.

  I worked with a brand team who loved flexible Webflow components. They kept responsiveness and brand integrity while non-developers built pages.

  Build components that protect the brand and speed up launches.
  What component caused the most problems when you first scaled?

column3: Let’s kick the week of with a discussion: Email adres on a website should: Click to copy? ór Click and open email client? Lets get down in the comments! 👇
column7:
It took one small test to decide what works for our jobs page.

  We A/B tested click-to-copy versus mailto on candidate pages for six weeks. Click-to-copy increased form starts for mobile users.

  Match the action to the page intent and audience device.
  Which pages on your site get the most mobile visitors?
column8:
Contrarian view: default mailto can break more experiences than it fixes.

  A B2B client had users stuck in email apps, losing tracking and context. Replacing mailto with copy-to-clipboard kept users in the flow and improved attribution.

  Choose the option that keeps users in your conversion funnel.
  Do you track drop-offs after mailto clicks?
column9:
Do you ask whether the email address supports action or information retrieval?

  I recommend copy-to-clipboard for quick reference pages like press or support. Use mailto for pages that expect a draft email from the user.

  Design the interaction to match user intent not habit.
  Which interaction do you see more often on competitor sites?

column3: Using Calendly on your website? Please. F*cking. Stop. Too many SaaS founders are silently killing their growth. How? By slapping on a  Calendly widget on their site, and call it a day. I get it. Calendly is easy. But without: - context- qualification- time constraints It’s just makes people think: “Why would I spent my precious time on a demo?” “What in the world can I expect?” No wonder no one books a call. It’s confusing as hel, and it doesn’t convince visitors. Here’s what to do instead ↓ 1. Dedicated booking page So it’s easier to track and will make iteration in the future easier. (also reduces noise in your data later)2. Add context to your booking pageExplain who you help and what happens on the call. Frame this around value, not just availability3. Add 1-2 qualifying questions (eg. industry, team size, goals) You don’t want every random person book a call. Being selective signals you understand who you are helping You’re showing you are tailoring the call to them and making the call useful instead of generic. One client of mine got a 20% conversion bump by creating a dedicated booking page. Another client reduced unqualified bookings with 46% You see. People don’t just book a call. They book an outcome. Ps. Ready to see what really blocks your websites conversion? Sent me a DM with “AUDIT”, and I’ll share all the details.
column7:
Adding Calendly often reduces clarity more than it helps.

  A client replaced the widget with a dedicated booking page and clear context. Within weeks their booking conversion rose by about 20 percent, and sales calls were more focused.

  Booking is a promise of outcome, not just a calendar.

  When did you last test the booking experience on your site?
column8:
Calendly is a scheduling tool, not a conversion strategy.

  I see teams equate availability with qualification so they skip context and screening. That usually creates noisy calendars and low show rates.

  First design the booking funnel: explain the value, add 1–2 qualifiers, then surface availability.

  What small qualifier could you add today to improve signal?
column9:
When did a simple widget become your demo strategy?

  It took me watching dozens of client calendars to realise context matters more than convenience. Adding a short qualifying form and a value-led page cut unqualified bookings significantly for multiple clients.

  Treat booking as a step in the funnel, not the finish line.

  Curious which two questions would filter your best leads?

column3: Does your SaaS website confuse visitors? Here are 3 ways to fix that ↓ As a SaaS founder or SaaS CMO, you know your SaaS product inside and out. → You know every feature by heart→ You understand the next steps instinctively → You speak the language of your product fluently That’s why the website makes total sense to you. But your visitors? They only see jargon and a bunch of fancy words. What’s obvious to you, Is confusing to them. It’s the blind spot that keeps showing up in places you might not expect: → Button labels that only make sense internally→ Copy that assumes too much context→ Visuals that look cool but don’t actually guide the user→ Layouts that follow your logic, not theirs The result? Confused visitors and lost leads. Here’s how I fix that ↓ 1͟.͟ ͟A͟p͟p͟l͟y͟ ͟t͟h͟e͟ ͟K͟I͟S͟S͟ ͟r͟u͟l͟e͟Keep it simple, stupid. If it feels like youre over-explaining. You’re doing it right.2͟.͟ ͟R͟u͟n͟ ͟A͟/͟B͟ ͟t͟e͟s͟t͟s͟ ͟o͟n͟ ͟y͟o͟u͟r͟ ͟c͟o͟n͟t͟e͟n͟t͟Some gaps are hard to detect. Test 2 - 3 variations of, for example, your value prop to discover if it’s clear and obvious. Let data give you insights.3͟.͟ ͟D͟o͟c͟u͟m͟e͟n͟t͟ ͟q͟u͟e͟s͟t͟i͟o͟n͟s͟ ͟f͟r͟o͟m͟ ͟s͟a͟l͟e͟s͟ ͟c͟a͟l͟l͟s͟Any time someone asks:“𝘞𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘥𝘰𝘦𝘴 𝘵𝘩𝘪𝘴 𝘮𝘦𝘢𝘯?”“𝘐𝘴 𝘵𝘩𝘪𝘴 𝘪𝘯𝘤𝘭𝘶𝘥𝘦𝘥?”That’s a sign your website didn’t do its job.Turn those questions into on-page answers. Remember Youre not building for you.You’re building for your user. Ps. Are you running a B2B SaaS business and want to increase your sign-up rate? DM “SaaS” and I will send you a video with the 3 biggest issues holding back your website.
column7:
It took me years to stop assuming founders see what visitors see.

  One SaaS client kept internal labels on primary CTAs. We ran three headline variations and found a clear winner in two weeks. The change made the next step obvious to new visitors.

  Simple tests and documented sales questions move the needle more than fancy design.

  Which page would you A/B test first?
column8:
Teams fix visuals while the copy still speaks internally.

  I see this pattern constantly: pretty layouts that explain features to peers, not outcomes to prospects. Shifting button labels and answering common sales questions on-page reduced confusion in several projects.

  Start with clarity, then polish the visuals.

  What internal phrase on your site would confuse a new visitor?
column9:
Which part of your site assumes too much product knowledge?

  I began collecting questions from sales calls and turning them into on-page answers. That practice exposed blind spots and made the site do the heavy lifting for discovery.

  You’re building for the user, not for the person who built the product.

  What’s one frequent sales question you could put on your homepage?
